<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870729-0049 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:City Gas Co. of Florida</HL><DD> 07/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CGFNATURAL GAS, PIPELINES (LNG) </IN><TEXT>   City Gas Co. of Florida was ordered by the U.S. District Court in Miami to pay $4.8 million to Consolidated Gas Co. of Florida Inc. for allegedly violating antitrust law by refusing to sell natural gas to Consolidated. The court also ordered City Gas, a Miami natural-gas utility, to sell gas to Consolidated at a reasonable price. The court rejected City Gas allegations of antitrust violations by Consolidated, a Miami liquefied-gas distributor. City Gas Chairman S.W. Langer called the ruling &quot;stupid, unbelievable,&quot; and said the utility would appeal. William J. Dunaj, a lawyer for Consolidated, called the decision &quot;landmark.&quot; </TEXT></DOC>